{"title_page": "La Pallice", "text_new": "'''La Pallice''' (also known as '''''grand port maritime de La Rochelle''''') is the commercial deep-water port of [[La Rochelle]], [[France]].\n\nDuring the [[Fall of France]], on 19 June 1940, approximately 6,000 [[Second Polish Republic|Polish]] soldiers in exile under the command of [[Stanis\u0142aw Sosabowski]]\narrived at La Pallice, from where they were evacuated to Great Britain - thus able to go on fighting till the end of the war.\n\nUnder the [[Military history of France during World War II|Nazi Occupation of France]], La Pallice was used as a [[U-boat base]] ({{ill|Base sous-marine de La Rochelle|fr}}) from October 1941 when the [[3rd U-boat Flotilla]] was moved there from its base in [[Kiel]]. La Pallice was subject to the [[allied siege of La Rochelle]] in 1944\u201345, which ended with [[Victory in Europe Day|the capitulation of Germany]].<ref name=\"Battlefields\"/> The large [[Submarine pen|submarine base]] built at that time still stands largely is not in use.<ref name=\"Battlefields\"/> It was used as a backdrop for the film ''[[Das Boot]]'' (1981)<ref name=\"La Pallice base\">{{cite book | chapterurl=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=U87-CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Hitler\u2019s Armed Forces Auxiliaries: An Illustrated History of the Wehrmachtsgefolge, 1933\u20131945 | publisher=McFarland | author=Lepage, Jean-Denis G.G. | year=2016 | pages=46 | isbn=1476620881 | chapter=Organisation Todt}}</ref> and ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]'' (1984).<ref name=\"Battlefields\">{{cite web | url=http://www.battlefieldsww2.com/la-pallice-u-boat-bunker.html | title=U-boat Base La Pallice | work=Battlefields | accessdate=October 5, 2017 | author=Ambrosius, Martin}}</ref>\n\nLa Pallice is equipped with oil unloading equipment, and mainly handles tropical wood. It is also the home of La Rochelle's fishing fleet, which was moved from the old harbour in the city centre during the 1980s.\n\n{{Wide image|LaPallicePanorama.jpg |1800px|Panorama of La Pallice industrial harbour, seen from [[\u00cele de R\u00e9]]}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.battlefieldsww2.com/la-pallice-u-boat-bunker.html German submarine base in La Pallice]\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in La Rochelle]]\n[[Category:German Navy submarine bases]]\n[[Category:Ports and harbours of France]]\n[[Category:Transport in Nouvelle-Aquitaine]]\n\n{{coord|46|09|30|N|1|13|40|W|type:landmark_region:FR|display=title}}\n\n{{CharenteMaritime-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''La Pallice''' (also known as '''''grand port maritime de La Rochelle''''') is the commercial deep-water port of [[La Rochelle]], [[France]].\n\nDuring the [[Fall of France]], on 19 June 1940, approximately 6,000 Polish soldiers in exile under the command of [[Stanis\u0142aw Sosabowski]]\narrived at La Pallice, from where they were evacuated to Great Britain - thus able to go on fighting till the end of the war.\n\nUnder the [[Military history of France during World War II|Nazi Occupation of France]], La Pallice was used as a [[U-boat base]] ({{ill|Base sous-marine de La Rochelle|fr}}) from October 1941 when the [[3rd U-boat Flotilla]] was moved there from its base in [[Kiel]]. La Pallice was subject to the [[allied siege of La Rochelle]] in 1944\u201345, which ended with [[Victory in Europe Day|the capitulation of Germany]].<ref name=\"Battlefields\"/> The large [[Submarine pen|submarine base]] built at that time still stands largely is not in use.<ref name=\"Battlefields\"/> It was used as a backdrop for the film ''[[Das Boot]]'' (1981)<ref name=\"La Pallice base\">{{cite book | chapterurl=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=U87-CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Hitler\u2019s Armed Forces Auxiliaries: An Illustrated History of the Wehrmachtsgefolge, 1933\u20131945 | publisher=McFarland | author=Lepage, Jean-Denis G.G. | year=2016 | pages=46 | isbn=1476620881